Wash and dry produce.

Finely dice @tomato{1}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from
greens. Core, deseed, and dice @long green pepper{1}.

== Southwest Creama ==

In a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{3%tablespoon}, @Southwest spice blend{1%tsp}
(2 tsp for 4 servings), @salt{} and @pepper{}. (You'll use the rest of the Southwest
Spice Blend later.) Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling
consistency.

== Tomato Salsa ==

In a separate small bowl, combine tomato, scallion whites, and @green salsa{1%TBSP}
(you'll use the rest later). Season with salt and pepper.

== Pork Tacos ==

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat. Add green pepper and season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until
softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Add @ground pork{10%ounce} and another drizzle of oil to same pan. Season with salt,
pepper, and @Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon} (remaining). Cook, breaking up meat
into pieces, until pork is browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> TIP: If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it out.

Add remaining @green salsa{6%ounce} to pan with pork; bring to a simmer over
medium-high heat. Cook until slightly thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4 servings) until melted. Season with
salt and pepper. Turn off heat.

Wrap @flour tortillas{6} in damp #paper towels{} and microwave until warm and
pliable, ~{30%seconds}.

Divide tortillas between plates and fill with pork mixture, @Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup},
salsa mixture, and crema. Sprinkle with scallion greens and serve.

> Ground Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.